            {"type": "p", "text": "Three things matter for partners."},
            {"type": "p_bold_lead", "lead": "Triggers in adult relationships are different from triggers in childhood.", "rest": "Children with RSD trigger on classroom corrections and peer comments. Adults with RSD trigger on what Gottman calls \"bids for connection that get ignored\" — delayed replies, neutral facial expressions, perceived sighs of frustration, the ambiguous tone of a text. The threshold is the same; the input changes."},
            {"type": "p_bold_lead", "lead": "Pursuit and withdrawal are both RSD responses.", "rest": "Some adults with RSD pursue — \"are you mad at me, what did I do, please tell me\" — until the partner reassures them. Others withdraw — silence, distance, an emotional wall. Both are coping strategies for the same neurological event. Recognizing which strategy your partner runs is the first step to responding usefully."},
            {"type": "p_bold_lead", "lead": "Repair attempts have to be explicit.", "rest": "John Gottman's research on long-term relationships found that the strongest predictor of relationship durability is the quality and frequency of repair attempts — small gestures or statements designed to prevent negativity from escalating. For partners managing RSD together, repair attempts have to be more explicit, more deliberate, and more frequent than they would be otherwise. Subtle repair signals don't register through the RSD filter."},
